<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-451-986  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 451 986.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Quarterly  March 1990 v14 n1 p26(17).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Expert systems: a question of liability? (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mykytyn, Kathleen; Mykytyn, Peter P., Jr.; Slinkman, Craig W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The development of expert systems has changed dramatically inrecent years based largely on concepts dealing with artificialintelligence.andP;  These efforts are evolving from very specific,academically oriented efforts, such as medical diagnosis, to moremanagerially oriented corporate issues.andP;  Unfortunately, manyproponents of these systems may be overlooking possible legalramifications related to both the development and use of thesesystems.andP;  A major issue concerns the establishment of liabilityfor the decisions and recommendations made by expert systems.andO;Some liabilities could include product liability and negligence.andO;All individuals involved with expert systems (knowledge engineers,domain experts, and users) are potentially subject to legalscrutiny.andP;  It behooves organizations involved with these systemsto investigate potential legal problems concerning them.andP;  As thesesystems become more pervasive, courts may look upon them for whatthey are: systems of knowledge and experience, not simply passivecomputer software.andP;  A framework is presented that traces thedevelopment of a product, legal issues related to the development,and normative measures that organizations can take to forestallpossible legal calamities.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of thepublisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Expert SystemsLegal IssuesArtificial IntelligenceMIS.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   A framework for product growth and legal impact. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>